1
00:00:00,740 --> 00:00:08,631
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato sambha sambhodasa.

2
00:00:08,651 --> 00:00:13,198
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:15,262 --> 00:00:23,934
So I just picked up on a discourse and it's concerned with how we discuss things with each other, how we talk to each other.

4
00:00:23,975 --> 00:00:29,682
So in this age of great polarization, I thought, well, let's see what the Buddha has to say.

5
00:00:33,088 --> 00:00:41,240
It comes from the Anguttanikā, which is a collection of the small discourses.

6
00:00:41,259 --> 00:00:42,561
And it starts off like this.

7
00:00:43,061 --> 00:00:46,066
There are mendicants, these three topics of discussion.

8
00:00:46,246 --> 00:00:46,767
What three?

9
00:00:48,408 --> 00:00:50,210
You might discuss the past.

10
00:00:50,491 --> 00:00:52,194
This is how it was in the past.

11
00:00:53,414 --> 00:00:54,817
You might discuss the future.

12
00:00:55,677 --> 00:00:57,320
This is how it will be in the future.

13
00:00:57,820 --> 00:00:59,383
And you might discuss the present.

14
00:00:59,701 --> 00:01:02,005
This is how it is at present.

15
00:01:02,424 --> 00:01:05,310
Now, at first, that seems a bit sort of obvious.

16
00:01:06,692 --> 00:01:08,975
But of course, there are three very different conversations.

17
00:01:09,697 --> 00:01:15,546
The first one is all about memory and about opinions about memory and what we thought had happened.

18
00:01:16,429 --> 00:01:20,915
The second one is all driven to some sort of future idea, some idealism.

19
00:01:21,367 --> 00:01:23,450
And there could be arguments about that.

20
00:01:24,012 --> 00:01:28,897
And the present, of course, is sort of an attempt to see things as they are.

21
00:01:29,037 --> 00:01:31,302
But everybody sees things differently.

22
00:01:31,802 --> 00:01:36,048
So there's all sorts of argumentation.

23
00:01:36,067 --> 00:01:43,799
So what the discourse does is it takes the process of discussion.

24
00:01:43,899 --> 00:01:47,123
The first one is the skill in questions.

25
00:01:48,875 --> 00:02:14,021
so you can see whether it's worth talking to somebody here they would say a person is the discourse says a person is competent to hold a discussion but what it means is whether it's worth you talking to them and remember that at that time when you read the discourses they didn't have recording machines remember so

26
00:02:14,710 --> 00:02:41,359
the way that you got people to be clear was to ask the question three times and to make sure that is is that what you mean and it was done either as two individuals or in a group so that the position taken was clear what was said was clear and that would undermine silly arguments and at that time they had a sort of

27
00:02:41,794 --> 00:02:45,721
imagination, which is called reproductive imagination, not like ours.

28
00:02:47,223 --> 00:03:01,264
If you see a car crash, you'll see it one way and then you won't be sure that you've seen it because you didn't record it fully and there'll be questions asked.

29
00:03:02,665 --> 00:03:07,954
In those times, they had what was called reproductive memory.

30
00:03:08,389 --> 00:03:12,933
imagination, and they were very good at remembering things.

31
00:03:14,675 --> 00:03:30,730
Even today at the 1956 Sixth Great Council held in Burma, there were six monks who knew all the scriptures, all the Abhidhamma and all the Vinaya, the rule of the monks.

32
00:03:30,911 --> 00:03:33,673
I mean, that's a massive amount of literature.

33
00:03:34,133 --> 00:03:35,594
They knew it off by heart.

34
00:03:36,300 --> 00:03:53,064
And when the questions came about certain passages in the scriptures, which were maybe not quite right or whatever, it was these people, these monks who became the experts who would quote from directly from the scriptures.

35
00:03:55,048 --> 00:04:02,038
OK, so just as an aside, by the way, it seems that the Brahmins,

36
00:04:02,643 --> 00:04:28,548
they teach their children the scriptures and learn them by heart and they're concerned with pronunciation only when they can learn that do they actually add the meaning of the words and only when they've got the words and the pronunciation together are they allowed to discuss what the scriptures say okay so here are the sorts of questions that somebody can ask

37
00:04:29,812 --> 00:04:40,047
So when a person is asked a question, if it needs to be answered categorically and they don't answer it categorically, then that shows they're not worth talking to.

38
00:04:40,487 --> 00:04:46,495
So one of the things that you might say in Buddhism is, is the Buddha impermanent?

39
00:04:46,997 --> 00:04:53,305
And if they prevaricate, yes, no, maybe and all that, then what we want is a clear statement.

40
00:04:53,425 --> 00:04:54,908
Yes, yes, it is.

41
00:04:55,596 --> 00:04:59,661
Another one is, is UK a European country?

42
00:04:59,901 --> 00:05:00,862
Now, I should say, yes.

43
00:05:01,463 --> 00:05:03,545
Lots of UK people don't think they are, I think.

44
00:05:05,567 --> 00:05:09,593
But that's what should be said, at least geographically.

45
00:05:12,516 --> 00:05:14,819
Now, the next sort of question might need analysis.

46
00:05:15,298 --> 00:05:18,182
So one regular question is, is Buddhism a religion?

47
00:05:18,583 --> 00:05:22,346
So then you have to ask, well, what do you mean by religion, right?

48
00:05:22,951 --> 00:05:31,141
Another one is when the Buddha is describing this whole idea of not-self, he starts off with control.

49
00:05:31,302 --> 00:05:33,285
How much of the body can you control?

50
00:05:33,785 --> 00:05:35,247
Is it under your control?

51
00:05:35,608 --> 00:05:37,870
Can you make it grow taller, etc.?

52
00:05:38,552 --> 00:05:44,980
So then you'd have to say, well, when he means control, he obviously means the body as an organism.

53
00:05:45,319 --> 00:05:47,043
But obviously I can move it around.

54
00:05:47,062 --> 00:05:51,067
I do have some ability to control it.

55
00:05:53,122 --> 00:05:56,406
And of course, what he's really pointing to is sickness, aging and death.

56
00:05:58,267 --> 00:06:02,752
Now, sometimes you ask a question, it needs a counter question.

57
00:06:03,552 --> 00:06:07,396
So one Dharma question would be, are the ear and nose the same?

58
00:06:07,755 --> 00:06:09,278
So you say, well, in what way?

59
00:06:09,718 --> 00:06:10,879
You say, well, in their function.

60
00:06:11,059 --> 00:06:11,839
Well, yes, they are.

61
00:06:11,860 --> 00:06:12,480
They're the same.

62
00:06:12,500 --> 00:06:13,641
They both perceive.

63
00:06:18,846 --> 00:06:20,548
These days, of course, we have this

64
00:06:21,187 --> 00:06:23,088
whole thing about immigration.

65
00:06:23,470 --> 00:06:27,033
So a question might be, should immigration be allowed to stay?

66
00:06:27,093 --> 00:06:32,581
Well, then you say, well, what type, you know, what are the types of immigrants that are coming to the country?

67
00:06:33,161 --> 00:06:34,523
And can we make distinctions?

68
00:06:39,870 --> 00:06:41,872
As a teacher, you see, a Vipassana teacher.

69
00:06:42,213 --> 00:06:44,735
So I might say to you, how's your practice going?

70
00:06:44,776 --> 00:06:45,877
And you say, oh, yeah, that's good.

71
00:06:46,478 --> 00:06:48,961
Now, if I'm a bad teacher, I'll say, oh, very good.

72
00:06:48,980 --> 00:06:49,961
I'll take your word for it.

73
00:06:51,375 --> 00:06:54,661
But if I'm a good teacher, then I'll say, well, in what way?

74
00:06:54,961 --> 00:06:56,863
And you say, well, my mind is more quiet.

75
00:06:56,923 --> 00:06:58,947
I'm able to see process more clearly.

76
00:06:59,406 --> 00:07:00,788
I say sadhu, sadhu.

77
00:07:01,389 --> 00:07:03,533
If you say to me, well, I'm feeling a lot happier.

78
00:07:03,653 --> 00:07:05,615
I say, no, it's not about happiness.

79
00:07:06,697 --> 00:07:07,619
That's the end product.

80
00:07:09,901 --> 00:07:13,247
And then there are questions that should be set aside.

81
00:07:13,326 --> 00:07:16,812
So in a conversation, somebody might ask you a personal question.

82
00:07:17,232 --> 00:07:21,298
So you don't have to answer that, you know, even if it seems to be relevant.

83
00:07:22,661 --> 00:07:28,226
Now, in the Buddhist teachings, there were 10 questions that he wouldn't answer.

84
00:07:29,108 --> 00:07:31,269
They are known as the avyāgata.

85
00:07:31,290 --> 00:07:36,673
They are the undeclared 10 statements or questions.

86
00:07:37,475 --> 00:07:39,956
So first of all, they run like this.

87
00:07:40,336 --> 00:07:41,538
Is the world eternal?

88
00:07:41,738 --> 00:07:43,720
Is the world not eternal?

89
00:07:43,740 --> 00:07:45,802
Is the world finite or is the world infinite?

90
00:07:47,584 --> 00:07:48,904
So that he wouldn't answer.

91
00:07:50,505 --> 00:07:52,348
I don't think he'd know, frankly.

92
00:07:54,218 --> 00:08:23,668
um although i have to say in the commentary on the visuddhimagga it does unfortunately say that the buddha knew the world was flat so this he didn't say anything about the world as uh as something objective out there his main interest was the world that we're creating moment after moment the next one is is the soul the same as the body

93
00:08:24,069 --> 00:08:27,273
Is the soul one thing and the body another?

94
00:08:27,874 --> 00:08:29,095
Now, he doesn't answer that.

95
00:08:29,615 --> 00:08:36,221
And it's something that I think is worth investigating on another little talk.

96
00:08:36,240 --> 00:08:39,804
So I won't go into that particular one.

97
00:08:40,465 --> 00:08:44,009
And then finally, there were four questions around a Tathagata.

98
00:08:44,028 --> 00:08:52,996
Remember, that's how he referred to himself, the one who had arrived, who had gone, who had completed the path.

99
00:08:53,855 --> 00:08:56,739
And it refers to any Arahant, really.

100
00:08:57,159 --> 00:09:00,144
So does a Tathagata exist after death?

101
00:09:01,706 --> 00:09:03,429
Does he not exist after death?

102
00:09:03,490 --> 00:09:04,892
This is known as the quadrilemma.

103
00:09:06,673 --> 00:09:10,580
Does a Tathagata both exist and not exist after death?

104
00:09:11,361 --> 00:09:12,342
And here's a headbanger.

105
00:09:12,984 --> 00:09:18,052
Does a Tathagata neither exist nor not exist after death?

106
00:09:18,812 --> 00:09:22,258
Well, not surprisingly, he didn't make an answer to that.

107
00:09:23,065 --> 00:09:31,091
The real reason, of course, was that people were thinking of the tatagata or a liberated one as a person, as a self.

108
00:09:32,092 --> 00:09:34,676
So he just, he didn't like those sorts of questions.

109
00:09:35,576 --> 00:09:38,438
He didn't like any questions that were speculative, basically.

110
00:09:40,841 --> 00:09:46,167
So now we move on to a different section, which is the skill in the conventions of conversation.

111
00:09:46,927 --> 00:09:51,991
So when a person is asked a question, if they're not consistent about their position,

112
00:09:52,495 --> 00:10:12,355
or what their position is and what it isn't, about what they propose, and then they change the subject, about speaking from what they know and not from some sort of fake position, and that it's appropriate to the procedure.

113
00:10:12,816 --> 00:10:20,764
So this is really when you're having a discussion with somebody, you're not speaking over each other.

114
00:10:22,144 --> 00:10:23,527
Politicians are very good at that.

115
00:10:24,027 --> 00:10:30,755
I was watching a BBC interview with Varoufakoulis, Varoufakoulis, I think that's his name, the Greek economist, some of you may know.

116
00:10:31,236 --> 00:10:33,099
And there was an economic lecturer there.

117
00:10:33,239 --> 00:10:35,962
She was from some Oxford or somewhere.

118
00:10:36,582 --> 00:10:37,845
And of course, the interviewer.

119
00:10:38,485 --> 00:10:41,529
And at first, he was asking the questions.

120
00:10:41,590 --> 00:10:43,692
They were answering it all, looked very civilized.

121
00:10:44,173 --> 00:10:48,118
And then right at the end, the three of them spoke all together.

122
00:10:48,537 --> 00:10:51,200
trying to crush the other.

123
00:10:51,640 --> 00:10:52,302
It's just weird.

124
00:10:53,703 --> 00:10:55,166
And of course, I didn't get a word of it.

125
00:10:58,330 --> 00:11:16,332
So when a person is asked the question, if they're consistent about their position, what their position is and what it isn't, about what they propose, about speaking from what they know and about the appropriate procedure, then that person is competent to hold a discussion.

126
00:11:21,341 --> 00:11:25,326
how people engage when being attacked.

127
00:11:26,287 --> 00:11:32,494
So you can know whether or not a person is competent to hold a discussion by seeing how they take part in a discussion.

128
00:11:33,115 --> 00:11:45,047
When a person is asked a question, if they dodge the issue, distract the discussion with irrelevant points, display annoyance, hate and bitterness, then that person is not competent to hold a discussion.

129
00:11:45,368 --> 00:11:45,847
So

130
00:11:46,908 --> 00:11:49,110
So that's politicians, isn't it?

131
00:11:49,211 --> 00:11:56,763
Dodging the issue, distracting it, saying something irrelevant and occasionally sort of getting a little bit uppity about things.

132
00:11:59,407 --> 00:12:10,403
So when a person is asked the question, if they don't dodge the issue, distract the discussion with irrelevant points or display annoyance, hate and bitterness, then that person, you know, we can talk to them.

133
00:12:12,746 --> 00:12:16,392
The next question is how people engage with confrontation.

134
00:12:16,777 --> 00:12:18,639
So afraid of being bettered.

135
00:12:21,202 --> 00:12:26,570
So you can know whether a person is competent to hold a discussion by seeing how they take part in a discussion.

136
00:12:27,351 --> 00:12:37,085
When a person is asked a question, if they intimidate, crush, mock and seize at trivial mistakes, then they're not competent to hold a discussion.

137
00:12:37,264 --> 00:12:38,667
In other words, don't talk to them.

138
00:12:39,710 --> 00:12:50,725
But when a person is asked a question, if they don't intimidate you, crush you, mock you, seize upon trivial mistakes, then it's worth talking to them.

139
00:12:50,745 --> 00:13:03,682
And often in conversation, it's about winning, not about finding some sort of truth, not about finding some sort of way of compromise, not even coming to a position of agreeing to differ.

140
00:13:04,043 --> 00:13:05,565
It's about who wins.

141
00:13:06,322 --> 00:13:14,870
I saw really quite a horrible discussion on YouTube between a university professor and Jordan Peterson.

142
00:13:15,571 --> 00:13:21,716
And somebody whom you'll know, I just can't bring his name to mind, but it was vicious.

143
00:13:22,056 --> 00:13:22,917
It was about woke.

144
00:13:23,798 --> 00:13:29,102
And the professor especially was very insulting, you know.

145
00:13:30,764 --> 00:13:33,527
But, yeah, what can you do?

146
00:13:34,908 --> 00:13:40,255
I think the other two, Jordan Peterson and the other fellow, I mean, Jordan Peterson, you know, is a right wing guru.

147
00:13:40,736 --> 00:13:42,318
And the other fellow was on the left.

148
00:13:43,942 --> 00:13:45,865
If I was any of those, I'd have just walked out.

149
00:13:47,366 --> 00:13:48,328
He's just insulting.

150
00:13:49,791 --> 00:13:52,394
OK, so now we have a general disposition.

151
00:13:53,096 --> 00:13:58,845
You can know whether or not a person has what's required by seeing how they take part in a discussion.

152
00:13:59,625 --> 00:14:03,312
If they actively listen, they have what's required.

153
00:14:05,434 --> 00:14:14,188
And if they know what they're talking about, well, actually, the next section is about the Four Noble Truths.

154
00:14:14,208 --> 00:14:22,923
But there the Buddha is actually stressing the fact, the ability to listen, you know, not to be afraid of actually what the person might say.

155
00:14:22,982 --> 00:14:29,373
Be open to the fact that your own position may be changed, may be nuanced.

156
00:14:29,894 --> 00:14:32,437
Often when we enter into a discussion about something,

157
00:14:32,788 --> 00:14:36,841
There's an underlying fear of being changed, of losing.

158
00:14:39,187 --> 00:14:41,554
So the next one is much more to do with the scriptures.

159
00:14:42,216 --> 00:14:45,245
It says, for someone...

160
00:14:46,035 --> 00:14:54,523
who has what's required, directly knows one thing, completely understands one thing, gives up one thing and realizes one thing.

161
00:14:54,864 --> 00:14:59,567
That one thing, of course, is Nibbana and the path to Nibbana.

162
00:14:59,587 --> 00:15:15,081
And here the Buddha points out that the purpose of all discussion, as far as he's concerned, and consultation, sitting close and listening well, is the liberation of the mind by not clinging, by not grasping,

163
00:15:18,200 --> 00:15:20,023
So finally, there's a sort of coda.

164
00:15:20,663 --> 00:15:30,201
Those who converse with hostility, too sure of themselves, arrogant, ignoble, attacking virtues, they look for flaws in each other.

165
00:15:31,261 --> 00:15:39,035
They rejoice together when their opponent speaks poorly, makes a mistake, becomes confused and is defeated.

166
00:15:39,436 --> 00:15:42,081
But the noble ones don't discuss like this.

167
00:15:43,023 --> 00:15:54,518
If an astute person wants to hold a discussion connected with the teaching and its meaning, the kind of discussion that the noble ones hold, then that wise one should start the discussion.

168
00:15:56,600 --> 00:16:10,498
Knowing when the time is right, neither hostile nor arrogant, not overexcited, contemptuous or aggressive, or with a mind full of jealousy, they speak from what they rightly know.

169
00:16:10,951 --> 00:16:13,614
They agree with what is well spoken.

170
00:16:14,174 --> 00:16:30,673
See, you know, actually praising the other, the person who has a contradictory idea, praising them or at least accepting when they've made a decent argument without criticizing what has been poorly said.

171
00:16:31,475 --> 00:16:39,303
They don't persist in finding faults, nor seizing on trivial mistakes, nor intimidating, nor crushing the other.

172
00:16:40,027 --> 00:16:43,211
Nor would they speak suggestively, snidely.

173
00:16:45,313 --> 00:16:49,119
Good people consult for the sake of knowledge and clarity.

174
00:16:50,541 --> 00:16:51,942
That's a really good statement.

175
00:16:52,464 --> 00:16:57,309
Good people consult for the sake of knowledge and clarity.

176
00:16:57,971 --> 00:16:59,933
That's how the noble ones consult.

177
00:17:00,434 --> 00:17:02,336
This is noble consultation.

178
00:17:03,177 --> 00:17:08,025
Knowing this, a wise person should consult without arrogance.

179
00:17:10,417 --> 00:17:15,194
So that's the final section of the discourse.

180
00:17:15,556 --> 00:17:20,192
And remember, we shouldn't take these discourses as a sort of final statements about these things.

181
00:17:20,492 --> 00:17:27,440
Even subjects like dependent origination crop up in various discourses from various angles.

182
00:17:28,961 --> 00:17:35,528
So it's not as though we take a discourse and say, well, that's everything to be said about discussion.

183
00:17:35,669 --> 00:17:36,269
Far from it.

184
00:17:37,892 --> 00:17:39,133
They're just pointers.

185
00:17:39,854 --> 00:17:48,643
And our task is to translate what we have understood back into our own lives and, of course, into society, especially these days.

186
00:17:49,045 --> 00:17:51,971
When, as you know, there's so much polarization.

187
00:17:53,993 --> 00:18:05,957
The Buddha himself, you know, when somebody reported to him what one of his monks or nuns had said, he would say, well, if you'd have asked me that question, I would have said the same thing.

188
00:18:07,674 --> 00:18:14,763
Okay, so now just before we finish off, I just want to point to three books and I'll put them on the website.

189
00:18:15,163 --> 00:18:20,790
The first one is, I don't know whether you can see it, is Nonviolent Communication.

190
00:18:23,173 --> 00:18:25,656
You can see that guy, just a minute.

191
00:18:25,676 --> 00:18:26,076
There we go.

192
00:18:28,740 --> 00:18:30,563
And, oops, what have I done?

193
00:18:32,105 --> 00:18:34,948
Ah, by Rosenberg.

194
00:18:35,266 --> 00:18:42,655
And that is really a very famous book and definitely worth reading about how to talk to people.

195
00:18:44,057 --> 00:18:47,563
The other one, I've not read it entirely, but I read little sections of it.

196
00:18:47,943 --> 00:18:49,685
It's called Difficult Conversations.

197
00:18:49,886 --> 00:18:50,667
Oops, just a minute.

198
00:18:50,688 --> 00:18:57,176
It's because of the, it's because of the, that's it.

199
00:18:58,499 --> 00:19:01,722
And it takes up little difficult, difficult conversations.

200
00:19:02,104 --> 00:19:02,865
Why is it doing that?

201
00:19:02,884 --> 00:19:03,185
I wonder.

202
00:19:03,645 --> 00:19:04,227
Oh, yeah.

203
00:19:04,392 --> 00:19:05,272
Difficult conversation.

204
00:19:05,313 --> 00:19:06,493
All right, I shall leave it like that.

205
00:19:07,255 --> 00:19:10,778
Finally, I don't think you'll be able to get this book, but you might do.

206
00:19:11,278 --> 00:19:12,641
It's called Bad Arguments.

207
00:19:13,761 --> 00:19:27,135
And it tells you all the silly, all the ways that people sort of don't answer your question, don't converse with you in a proper manner and just cause confusion and anger usually.

208
00:19:28,897 --> 00:19:30,078
So very good.

209
00:19:30,515 --> 00:19:45,789
I hope this little discourse is of some use to you in your life and in society and is just part and parcel of your path to complete and full liberation from suffering sooner rather than later.

